<DOC><DOCNO> AP881020-0276 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-20-88 1224EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Airlines     10-20 0190</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Earns-Airlines,0198</SECOND><HEAD>AMR's Profit Up 72.5 Percent in Third Quarter</HEAD><DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   AMR Corp. reported a 72.5 percent jump in itsthird-quarter profit from a year earlier, which it attributedmainly to strong growth in passenger traffic and yield.   The parent of American Airlines said Wednesday that its netincome for the third quarter jumped to $150.3 million, or $2.50 ashare, from $87.1 million, or $1.41 a share, a year earlier.   Third-quarter revenue rose 17.9 percent, to $2.33 billion from$1.97 billion.   American's yield, the amount of revenue per passenger mile,increased by 9.9 percent from the third quarter of 1987. Apassenger mile represents one paying passenger flown one mile andis used to determine an airline's capacity.   ``Strong growth in both traffic and yield, coupled witheffective cost control and lower fuel prices, resulted in our bestthird-quarter earnings ever,'' said AMR Chairman and PresidentRobert L. Crandall.   In the first nine months of the year, AMR's net income rose to$360.1 million, or $5.98 a share, from $199.2 million, or $3.30 ashare.   Nine-month revenue rose 21.5 percent, to $6.46 billion from$5.32 billion.</TEXT></DOC>